Reading any old psychoanalysis author, e.g. Wilhelm Reich, makes it very clear that the "material conditions" for psychoanalysis to be coherent simply no longer occur. Reading the particular cases and no one's early life even remotely resembles them at all.

Each case involved a bizarre mix of having to sleep in the same room as your parents having sex up to teenage age, using chamber pots to excrete and urinate, having "terrifying" religious art of e.g. Isaac being sacrificed in the house. No one even remotely lives like this today.

It required a pathological combination of primitive material conditions like lack of living space, no sanitation, combined with high European culture allowing for depth of experience. Today you have your own room and a bathroom. The toilet stands a porcelain monument to progress.

A friend said in the 18th century E. Swedenborg used to build experimental lighter-than-air aircraft (e.g. proto-dirigibles) and paid Laplanders to pilot them. It's important as a scientist to have a cohort of friendly minorities nearby that you can bribe to test your inventions.

Arthur Jones the Nautilus machine inventor also built a submarine at one point and paid some guy to test it out. It just sunk down, but the guy managed to break free and escaped before drowning. "Me test it? No way, Jose." He also built a "functional machinegun" when he was 12.
